Providers and HTTP client

App providers

React context providers used at the app root (e.g. QueryClientProvider, theme, tooltips) must live under src/providers/, one concern per file when practical (e.g. query-client-provider.tsx, app-providers.tsx).
src/app/layout.tsx should stay thin: compose providers by importing a single AppProviders (or equivalent) from src/providers/, not inlining multiple providers in the layout file.

HTTP client

Browser-facing API calls use src/lib/http-client.ts: apiRequest, ApiError, and shared response parsing — not ad hoc fetch in components for the same patterns.
Feature-specific endpoints belong next to that feature (e.g. src/features/chat/api/) and call apiRequest; keep request/response shapes in feature types/ files.

TanStack Query

All client-side HTTP reads/writes that load or mutate app data go through TanStack Query (useQuery, useMutation, useInfiniteQuery, queryClient.fetchQuery / prefetchQuery when imperative). Do not call apiRequest or fetch from "use client" components except inside queryFn / mutationFn (or equivalent wrappers). apiRequest stays the transport; React Query owns when and how it runs.
QueryClient creation and defaults live only in src/providers/query-client-provider.tsx next to QueryClientProvider (same file — no separate lib/query-client module for the client instance).
Use useQueryClient for invalidateQueries, removeQueries, etc., inside hooks or components under the provider.

Query and mutation hooks (strict)

Do not call useQuery, useMutation, useInfiniteQuery, or useSuspenseQuery directly inside components (.tsx files under components/, app/, etc.). Those primitives belong only in feature hook modules.
One React Query call per file: each file under src/features/<feature>/hooks/ exports exactly one custom hook that wraps a single useQuery / useMutation / useInfiniteQuery (or re-exports a thin composition that still maps one logical server operation).
Naming: use useFetch… for reads (e.g. useFetchChats, useFetchChatDetail) and useMutate… for writes (e.g. useMutateCreateChat, useMutateDeleteChat). Import these hooks into components; components orchestrate UI and call mutateAsync / data / isPending, not raw TanStack hooks.
Exception: useQueryClient() may be used in components for cross-cutting invalidateQueries / removeQueries when not already folded into a mutation hook.

Client persistence

See.cursor/rules/client-persistence-zustand.mdc: localStorage / sessionStorage go through Zustand (with persist when saving to the browser), with feature code under src/features/<feature>/store/.
